Issues.Body:
Hi,
I just made a small thing that I think could be provided by angular API, but I'm not comfortable enough to contribute myself.
Basically I recently learned that you shouldn't call function in html templates, otherwise they are called many times in lifecycle and can cause performance issues. So you're supposed to create a pipe instead, and the pipe's "transform" method is in charge of calling the function you need on your object.
I figured that creating a brand new pipe for each function I need to call is not efficient, not reusable . So I made a generic pipe that takes function name and parameters as parameter. I think it'd be nice to have this implemented in Angular API as one of the basic pipes.

Here is my code :
```
import { Pipe, PipeTransform } from '@angular/core';

@Pipe({
  name: 'function'
})
export class FunctionPipe implements PipeTransform {

  transform(value: any, name: string, ...args: any): any {
    if (value && name && typeof(value[name]) === 'function') {
      return value[name](...args);
    }
    return null;
  }

}
```

And usage (in this example, item is of custom type Item and I need to display a value calculated by the function priceWithTaxes which takes tax % as parameter.
` <td>{{ item | function:'priceWithTaxes':30 | currency:'EUR' }}</td>`

#### What is the expected behavior?

Material components work in Internet Explorer the same way they do in Chrome/Firefox etc.

#### What is the current behavior?

The `ɵsetClassMetadata` method takes the properties of the component/directive as a parameter and with the Material components it contains duplicate properties because it uses the get and set feature of ES6 (I assume).

The output for the CdkTrapFocus looks like this.
```
ɵngcc0.ɵsetClassMetadata(CdkTrapFocus, [{
    type: Directive,
    args: [{ selector: '[cdkTrapFocus]', exportAs: 'cdkTrapFocus' }]
  }], 
  function () { ... },
   {
    _elementRef: [], _focusTrapFactory: [], _previouslyFocusedElement: [], _document: [], focusTrap: [],
    enabled: [{
      type: Input,
      args: ['cdkTrapFocus']
    }], 
  enabled: [], 
  autoCapture: [{
      type: Input,
      args: ['cdkTrapFocusAutoCapture']
    }], 
  autoCapture: [], 
  ngOnDestroy: [], ngAfterContentInit: [], ngDoCheck: []
});
```
As you can see the enabled and autoCapture properties are duplicated.
Now this is absolutely no problem with Chrome or Firefox or any other modern Browser but IE11 does not like this when running in strict mode with `"use strict"` (which is automatically added to the webpack bundle).

IE throws the following error
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/11866278/58024965-ae471580-7b13-11e9-885c-e1089efb9959.png)
Which translates to: Multiple definitions of a property are not allowed in strict mode.

#### What are the steps to reproduce?
Clone, npm install, ng s and open in Internet Explorer
https://github.com/M4R1KU/material-strict-mode

#### Which versions of Angular, Material, OS, TypeScript, browsers are affected?
Angular CLI: 8.0.0-rc.4
Node: 12.0.0
OS: win32 x64
Angular: 8.0.0-rc.4
... animations, cli, common, compiler, compiler-cli, core, forms
